<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="relative z-10 mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 py-16 sm:py-24">
  <div class="text-center mb-16">
    <h2 class="font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
      Frequently asked
      <span style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, oklch(0.76 0.13 280), oklch(0.65 0.20 300)); -webkit-background-clip: text; -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;">questions</span>
    </h2>
  </div>

  <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-list">
    <details class="group rounded-xl ring-1 ring-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-card)] transition-all hover:ring-[var(--color-primary)]/20">
      <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-5 text-sm font-semibold [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
        Is OpenCauldron really free?
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-45 text-[var(--color-muted)]"><path d="M12 5v14"/><path d="M5 12h14"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-muted)]">
        Depends on how you run it. <strong>Self-host</strong> is free and source-available under the Sustainable Use License — you only pay providers like Google or Replicate directly for AI model API usage with your own keys. <strong>Cloud</strong> is free during invite-only beta; paid tiers will come later, and you can always bring your own provider keys to keep costs predictable.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="group rounded-xl ring-1 ring-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-card)] transition-all hover:ring-[var(--color-primary)]/20">
      <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-5 text-sm font-semibold [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
        What API keys do I need?
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-45 text-[var(--color-muted)]"><path d="M12 5v14"/><path d="M5 12h14"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-muted)]">
        You only need keys for the providers you want to use. For example, a Google AI API key gives you access to Imagen 4 and Veo. A Replicate token unlocks Flux Pro. You can start with just one provider and add more as needed.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="group rounded-xl ring-1 ring-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-card)] transition-all hover:ring-[var(--color-primary)]/20">
      <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-5 text-sm font-semibold [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
        Can I add custom models?
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-45 text-[var(--color-muted)]"><path d="M12 5v14"/><path d="M5 12h14"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-muted)]">
        Yes. OpenCauldron has a provider registry that makes it straightforward to add new models. You can fork the repo and add any model that has an API. We also welcome PRs to add new providers to the main project.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="group rounded-xl ring-1 ring-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-card)] transition-all hover:ring-[var(--color-primary)]/20">
      <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-5 text-sm font-semibold [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
        How is billing handled?
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-45 text-[var(--color-muted)]"><path d="M12 5v14"/><path d="M5 12h14"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-muted)]">
        On <strong>self-host</strong>, OpenCauldron doesn't handle billing — your API keys are charged directly by each provider at their standard rates. On <strong>Cloud</strong>, you'll see provider costs the same way plus a monthly subscription for the hosted convenience (free during beta). Either way, the built-in usage dashboard breaks down every generation's cost by user, model, and brand.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="group rounded-xl ring-1 ring-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-card)] transition-all hover:ring-[var(--color-primary)]/20">
      <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-5 text-sm font-semibold [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
        Where is my data stored?
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-45 text-[var(--color-muted)]"><path d="M12 5v14"/><path d="M5 12h14"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-muted)]">
        On <strong>self-host</strong>, everything stays on your infrastructure — prompts and metadata in your PostgreSQL database, generated assets in your Cloudflare R2 bucket (or any S3-compatible storage). The self-hosted build never phones home or collects telemetry. On <strong>Cloud</strong>, your data lives in our managed PostgreSQL and R2 with per-workspace isolation — same code as self-host, just running for you.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="group rounded-xl ring-1 ring-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-card)] transition-all hover:ring-[var(--color-primary)]/20">
      <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-5 text-sm font-semibold [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
        Can I use it without self-hosting?
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-45 text-[var(--color-muted)]"><path d="M12 5v14"/><path d="M5 12h14"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-muted)]">
        Yes — <strong>OpenCauldron Cloud</strong> is the hosted version of the studio. Sign in with Google, get a workspace, start generating — no Docker, no setup. It's in invite-only beta right now; request a spot from the Cloud toggle at the top of the page. Prefer to run your own? Docker takes a few minutes — see the installation docs.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="group rounded-xl ring-1 ring-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-card)] transition-all hover:ring-[var(--color-primary)]/20">
      <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-5 text-sm font-semibold [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
        What license is OpenCauldron under?
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-45 text-[var(--color-muted)]"><path d="M12 5v14"/><path d="M5 12h14"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-muted)]">
        OpenCauldron is released under the <a href="https://github.com/opencauldron/opencauldron/blob/main/LICENSE" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[var(--color-primary)] hover:underline">Sustainable Use License</a> — the same license n8n uses. It's source-available: free for any internal business, personal, or non-commercial use, free to fork, modify, and contribute back. The one thing it prevents is third parties selling it as a competing commercial service. This keeps the project sustainable while staying open to almost everyone who wants to use or improve it.
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>
</section>
